AGI - EU Heads of State or Government - excluding Hungary - approved the five conditions for peace in Ukraine: "With a view to the new impetus for negotiations which should lead to such a global, just and lasting peace, the European Council stresses the importance of the following principles: (a) there can be no negotiations on Ukraine without Ukraine; (b) there can be no negotiations affecting European security without the involvement of Europe. The security of Ukraine, Europe, transatlantic and global are interconnected; c) any truce or ceasefire may take place only as part of the process leading to a global peace agreement; (d) any such agreement must be accompanied by solid and credible security guarantees for Ukraine that contribute to discouraging future Russian aggression; e) peace must respect the independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity of Ukraine." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"In the light of the negotiations for global, just and lasting peace, the European Union and the Member States are ready to contribute further to security guarantees based on their respective competences and abilities, in line with international law, also exploring the possible use of common security and defence policy instruments (Csdp). Security guarantees should be undertaken together with Ukraine, as well as with partners who share the same ideals and with NATO." It is explained in the conclusions of the EU summit on Ukraine, approved by 26 Member States excluding Hungary. "The European Council recalls that all military support and security guarantees for Ukraine will be provided in full compliance with the security and defence policy of certain Member States and taking into account the security and defence interests of all Member States," reads again in the text.&nbsp;
<h2>Intensify emergency military aid Kiev</h2>
"The European Council has re-examined its work on the provision of military support for Ukraine. In addition to the funds already committed for Ukraine for this year, it welcomes the availability of Member States to urgently intensify efforts to meet the pressing military and defence needs of Ukraine, in particular the provision of air defence systems, ammunition and missiles, the supply of training and equipment necessary for Ukrainian brigades, and other requirements that Ukraine can have." It reads in the conclusions of the EU summit on Ukraine, approved by 26 Member States excluding Hungary. "It emphasizes in this regard the important role of the European Union's military service mission in support of Ukraine (Eumam Ukraine). The European Council calls on the Council to carry out its work on initiatives, in particular the High Representative, in order to coordinate greater EU military support for Ukraine, including the component of the military needs of the Era del G7 initiative," added.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Costa: It is not divided; Hungary has been isolated
"The difference is that 26 countries believe that the path to peace is to strengthen the ability to defend Ukraine. Hungary has isolated itself from that consent. She's alone. An isolated country does not mean division. The 26 are united by the common desire to continue to support Ukraine, as we have done since the first day, on February 24, 2022, and we will continue together." The President of the European Council, Antonio Costa, declared this at the press conference at the end of the European Council.
&nbsp;
"On Ukraine we remain with strong support from 26 of the 27 member states in our common position. Hungary has a different strategic approach to Ukraine, but this means that Hungary is isolated among the 27 and we respect its position, but it is one out of 27 and 26 are more than one", he added.
